{"/service/ndnp/mnhi/batch_mnhi_motocross_ver01/data/sn90059182/00513689548/1938031001/0092.xml":{"full_text":"THE ELY MINER\nTHE ELY MINER\nPETER SCHAEPER, Publisher.\nTOntered at the Postofflce at Ely, Min\nnesota, as Second Class Matter.\nMember of the National Editorial\nAssociation; Minnesota Editorial Asso\nciation and the St. Louis County Press\nAssociation.\nSTUART SCHAEFER, Managing Editor\nI refill \"\u2018pH\nOn This Occasion\n(Continued from Page One)\nstate system alone, Mr. Elsberg\nsaid, if laid around the rim of\nthe United States, would en\ncircle the country with enough\nmileage of modern all-weather\nhighway remaining to run from\nNew Orleans to the Twin Cities\nto Winnipeg and thence to Sit\nka, Alaska. It costs the state\napproximately $8,000,000 an\nnually to maintain this system.\nThe railroads of the country\nlast year bought materials, sup\nplies and fuel amounting to\n$900,000,000 in 12,174 cities\nand towns in 2,637 counties in\n48 states of the Union. The 81\ncounties out of 87 in Minnesota\nand their 291 cities and towns\nshared in the distribution of\nthis immense sum. During\n1929 and 1930 railway pur\nchases of the necessities men\ntioned averaged $1,184,000,000\nannually. In the five years\nfrom 1931 to 1935 this yearly\naverage dropped to $559,819,-\n800. These figures were re\ncently presented to a special\nsenate committee investigating\nunemployment and relief. It\nwas pointed out that increased\nrevenues and a return of nor-\nmal traffic would bring re\nsumption in railroad supply\nbuying in large volume which\nin turn, would stimulate indus\ntrial activity throughout the na\ntion and the re-employment of\nthousands of workers.\nIt was also pointed out that\nto build one freight car, ma\nterial was required from 31 dif\nferent states and provide 1,987\nman-hours of employment\u2014ap-\nproximately a year\u2019s work for\none man. To build one loco-\nmotive provides 50 men with\nfulltime work for one year and\nrequires materials drawn from\nmore than thirty states.\nA survey of dormant bank\naccounts which have lain idle\nfor 20 years or more has re\nvealed that $107,559.50 is\nbeing carried by 106 Minnesota\nbanks in abandoned deposits.\nThe report is the result of the\nAbandoned Bank Deposit act\npassed by the last legislature,\nunder which all banks are re\nquired to report to the attorney\ngeneral all accounts of $lO or\nmore which have remained in\nactive for 20 years. Besides\nthe accounts containing $lO or\nmore, banks reporting to Attor\nney General William S. Ervin\nlisted thousands of accounts\nhaving less than $lO on de\nposit. Reports submitted by\nthe banks are on file in Attor\nney General Ervin\u2019s office and\nopen to public inspection for\nall those interested in locating\nabandoned accounts.\nStafford King, in his usual\nstraight from the shoulder\njg'.'\nPROSPERITY NIGHT!\nBingo Game\nSaturday Evening at 8 o\u2019clock\nOdd Fellows Hall\nFirst 15 Games for 25 Cents\nLADIES AND GENTLEMEN INVITED. FUN FOR\nGroceries Given. Door Prizes. Free Games.\nerpueg. Trtccf\nmanner, hit Governor Benson\na resounding slap on the\nknuckles over the governor\u2019s\nrecent criticism of A. W. Roh\nweder, Duluth, head of the\nMinnesota Safety Committee.\nFrom a hospital bed in Roches\nter, King dictated an address\nwhich was read before approxi\nmately 500 men attending the\nfinal session of the industrial\nsafety school in Duluth. Roh\nweder was drafted by the late\nGovernor Olson to head safety\nwork in the state and made a\nsuccess of his job\u2014and without\npay. He was replaced by one\nof Benson\u2019s cronies at a fat\nsalary.\nSeveral of the Legion Posts\nhave taken up the fight owing\nto Congressman Bernard\u2019s at\ntack on W. G. McDunnough,\nDuluth district WPA adminis\ntrator. McDunnough was ar\nrested at International Falls for\ntelling WPA strikers what he\nthought of them in language\nmore forcible than polite. Ber\nnard is seeking his removal on\nthe grounds that the adminis\ntrator had \u201cintimidated and\nabused WPA workers.\u201d The\ncase being tried today at the\nFalls is evidently considered a\nvery serious one, the judge hav\ning allowed McDunnough his\nliberty upon posting the munifi\ncent sum of $25. McDunnough\nis peculiar. He insists that men\ndo something for the money\nthey are getting.\nAfter Congressman Bernard\nfinishes the regulation of the\nSpanish war; the organization\nof the CIO, and one or two\nother activities equally as im\nportant to a member of the U.\nS. congress, he might pay some\nattention to serving the Eighth\nDistrict for which he is being\npaid SIO,OOO a year and perq\u2019s.\nNow that Seadlund has ad\nmitted the cold blooded murder\nof his kidnap victim, also the\nmurder of Seadlund\u2019s partner\nin the crime and has expressed\nthe desire to die rather than\nimprisonment for a long term\nof years, what is keeping the\nauthorities?\nTHE AMERICAN LEGION.\nEvery once in awhile the question as\nto why and wherefore of the American\nLegion is brought up. National Com\nmander Daniel J. Doherty, in a recent\naddress, made it quite plain as to the\naims and objects of this patriotic or-\nMarch 12th\nat the\nYOUNG AND OLD.\nIndian\nprints /n -me. i\nplant upe op our fv) S\nLAN6UA6E. f J 3 \u2018g*\ntobacco, 1 j|S\nSQiLbs/i.fePS/'/nrnon, Tneu'z.e &kE||\nJ Z FEW HUNTERS\n''l 1 WHO COULD\nI A GET A \u25a0RUT I\nft; MOOSE\nzv\ni sjaiai t,ai E\n7 /5 S?'?'<\ni f\\ I &Y\nI OUT INTO THE\nDEEP WOODS,\nI f j I AVO LISTENING\nW I 1 7TO THE HUMMING /W\n17 FIGURE IN THE DEVELOP-\nt HIS PREY. a NT F NORTHWEST, WHO AMWST\nHOSTILITY AND CRAFT OF THE\nBritish upheld the dignity of the\n00 E D WAR o U S. ON THE AbRTHWESTERN FRONTIER*\nOl itIC.E.IA-\u2019 TvWf 1 VD aY WS F ,K TREATMENT of the\nIndians spied the country from a\ndisastrous war. In /bio, remade\nf I K AN EXPEDITION UP THE MISSISSIPPI\n\\River as far as Cass Lake,which\n/N \\/S NAMED /N H/S HONOR. 1\n7\nganization. The commander in setting\nforth the aims of the Legion said:\nWidows and Orphans\nIn no event shall the widows and\norphans of World war veterans be with\nout government protection.\nUniversal Service\nA firm demand for universal service\nlegislation in this session of congress,\nproviding for an equal distribution of\nthe burdens of war, with special priv\nileges and profits for none.\nRehabilitation\nAdequate care and protection for\nevery disabled World war veteran as\nthe sacred duty of the federal govern\nment, and not as a function of private\ncharity.\nEmployment\nA nation-wide campaign in co-opera\ntion with industrial, labor and civic\norganizations to find or create jobs for\nthe re-employment of men over 40.\nrigid enforcement and broad extension\nof federal, state and municipal veterans\u2019\npreference laws, and provision by con\ngress for a census of unemployed vet\nerans to ascertain the reasons for and\nthe duration of their employment.\nNational Defense\nAdequate safeguards on land, sea and\nin the air, to insure the peace of\nAemrica.\nAmericanism\nContinued as a primary activity.\nVigilant opposition to subversive ele\nments in America. Investigation by\ncongress of organizations within the\nUnited States militantly serving other\nnations. Defense of basic American\nrights, particularly personal liberty, pri\nvate property, religious freedom, home\nand family, contract rights and obliga\ntions. Immediate restoration of regard\nfor fundamental legal rights and reme\ndies in industrial disputes. Promotion\nof education and youth training, in\ncluding Sons of the American Legion\nactivities, boy\u2019s state junior baseball,\nBoy Scouts and highway safety educa\ntion. Disaster relief organization. In\ndividual and collective community ser\nvice.\nChild Welfare\nStrengthening of activities to assure\nholding and improving existing gains\nfor children of veterans. Increased in\nstruction and services to the depart\nments to keep members informed of\nthe federal and state benefits of the\nchild welfare provisions of the social\nsecurity act, and to bring improvement\nin administration.\nPeace\nA definite three point peace program\nembracing a universal service act, ade\nquate national defense, and a proper\nneutrality policy, supplemented by a\ndetermination to promote good will on\nearth and combat propaganda of inter\nnational hate.\nLaw and Order\nDefinite nation-wide action, based on\ncareful study, to curb juvenile delin\nquency. Redoubling of efforts to -bring\nabout passage -by all states of the four\nmodel acts drafted by the interstate\ncrime commission.\nConservation\nRestoring useful wild life of America\nby the protection of its environment.\n\u201cWorking together,\u201d says Commander\nDoherty in a final comment, \u201cwe can\naccomplish these things.\u201d\nTOWNSHIPS LEAD THE\nWAY.\nMinnesota townships elected town of\nficers and set tax levies for the coming\nyear at the annual meetings held Tues\nday. Discussion of tax problems fea\ntured many of the meetings, some con\nsidering road problems, such as year\nround open roads.\nTownships in the state have earned\nthe title as \u201cthe most economical units\nin the government,\u201d because of the fact\nthat town levies throughout Minnesota\nwere reduced from $9,000,000 in 1930, to\n$5,000,000 two years ago. Increases last\nyear were due largely to road rises and,\nin some cases, relief problems.\nSpeaking on township problems in a\ntalk preceding township elections, Jas.\nP. McDonnell, president of the Minne\nsota Taxpayers association, declared:\n\u201cPersonally I believe the townships fill\na useful place in training citizens for\ngovernment. The township is closest\nto the people. Ido not believe that any\neconomies could -be made by turning\nthe business of twonships over to county\ngovernment.\u201d\nHe cited as an example that while\ntownships spent about six million in\nthe year, the total cost of state and\nlocal government in Minnesota exceeds\n$200,000,000 a year. \u201cUnder township\nrule, the farmer decides for himself just\nhow much he can afford to pay for\ncommunity costs. Here the taxpayer\nhas direct representation when levies\nare made. When it becomes necessary\nto economize, he does so.\n\u201cFarmers who live in townships ought\nto know what they need better than any\noutsider. They are familiar with every\nELY, MINNESOTA\nTOWER STATION\nWILL REMAIN\nConservation Commission Says\nThat Forestry Station Will\nContinue at Tower.\nIt now develops that the news of the\nabolishment of the Tower state forestry\nstation was premature and that nothing\nso drastic was contemplated.\nIn a letter from the conservation de\npartment, the rumor was denied and\nassurances were made that the station\nwould remain in Tower although the\narea supervisor is located at Orr and\nthat Tower will remain the district\nheadquarters. In a letter from the\ncommission it was stated:\n\u201cThe director of forestry is making\nsome changes in the boundaries of the\nold Tower district, but the area around\nTower and the Superior National Forest\nwill continue to be a ranger district,\nand as far as we know, Tower will con\ntinue as the district headquarters, under\nthe general supervision of an area\nsupervisor at Orr. I assure you it will\nbe the aim of the department to pro\nvide adequate quarters at Tower for\nthe activity there with a maximum\nmaintenance of equipment necessary.\u201d\nWELL KNOWN LADY DIES.\nMrs. Louise C. Porteus, well known in\nthis city, at one time being a resident\nhere and very prominent in Eastern\nStar circles, both here and at Tower,\ndied at her home in Tower, Tuesday\nmorning. She was 85 years of age and\nhas resided in Tower since 1901. She\nhas been a member of the Star order\nfor 50 years and past matron of the\nTower lodge. She is survived by two\nchildren, Mrs. Enice Burgess, publisher\nof the Tower News, and William G.\nSmith, Tower. Surviving also are four\ngrandchildren and three sisters in Tor\nonto, Canada. The funeral will be held\nthis afternoon from the Episcopal\nchurch at Tower.\nGun Sale to Be\nHeld in August.\nHarry E. Speakes, director of the di\nvision of game and fish, announces that\nthe conservation department sale of\nconfiscated guns will be held in Aug\nust or early part of September.\nThe sale formerly was held in March,\nbut this year is scheduled for the\nlater date, which is more seasoned for\nhunting equipment, and weather and\nroad conditions will permit rural resi\ndents to attend the sale.\nPersons from whom seizure is made\nmay make application to the division\nof game and fish and redeem their\nseized equipment at the appraised\nvalue. Redemption may be made at\nany time after appraisals are made.\nmile of road in the district. They know\ntheir own needs and their personal\nlimitations. They will not make levies\nthat they cannot pay. And local costs\nare watched as closely as their creamery\nchecks,\u201d Mr. McDonnell stated.\n\u201cIf townships were eliminated, com\npetition would develop between town\nships for county money, just as there\nis now competition between counties\nfor state aids, and in the states for\nFederal aids. This would likely result\nin much higher town costs. Farmers\nprefer to attend to their own town\nbusiness. They do not want to be\nobliged to search out engineers at a\ndistance every time they wish to have\na chuckhole filled down the road,\u201d Mr.\nMcDonnell pointed out.\n9 \"YOU THRILL TO LIVE, EAGER POWER-RE LAX IN 9\n9 RESTFUL COMFORT-REL YON THE LATEST SA FETY 9\n9 FEATURES, FROM KNEE-ACTION WHEELS TO H\n9 BIG, ROOMY FISHER BODY, HERE ARE ALL THE 9\n9 ESSENTIALS FOR REAL MOTORING ENJOYMENT 9\n-w 5\nM gtWftL\n.yr k i'\nI bk,\ngjgEWKL j\nA GENERAL\n1 ,de jt. f _lift..if-AM\nForest Chevrolet Company,\nEly, Minnesota.\nFORMER REIDENT DIES.\nFollowing the death of his brother\ntwo weeks ago, Thomas C. Grierson,\naged 75, died at his home in Eveleth,\nMonday, of a heart attack. Decased\nwas a resident of this city about 1915.\nHe came to Tower in 1880 and was en\ngaged in the building business. He has\nbeen a resident of Eveleth since 1895.\nThe funeral was held yesterday. Sur\nviving are two sons, Thomas, Jr., and\nRussell, of Eveleth. Russell is the son\nin-law of Mr. and Mrs. Fred Neff of\nthis city. Seven grandchildren also sur\nvive besides three sisters, Mrs. J. D.\nLamont, Virginia; Mrs. George Meade\nand Mrs. George Rich of Duluth.\nRebekahs Hear District\nPresident at Meeting.\nMrs. Pearl Stuart of -Galumet, dis\ntrict president of the Rebekah lodge,\nmet with Vermilion Lodge No. 8, on\nTuesday evening. Mrs. Stuart was ac\ncompanied by Mrs. Hazel Hycka, a past\nnoble grand of Calumet.\nThe district president was here on\none of her regular visits to lodges in\nthe district. She addressed the local\nRebekahs on the aims and objects of\nthe order.\nAmerica\u2019s Greatest\nFood Authority Now\nWrites for This Paper\nC. Houston Goudiss\nWe announce with pride a new\nfeature in this issue, \u201cWhat You\nEat and Why,\u201d by C. Houston\nGoudiss, noted food authority, radio\nspeaker, author and lecturer, fa\nmous as the man who knows food\n\u201cfrom soil to serving, from table\nto tissue.\u201d\nOne of these articles will appear\neach week, and we know housewives\nand mothers will look forward to\nthem for the accurate, worthwhile\ninformation they contain on foods\nand their relation to health. This\nis not a recipe column Mr. Goudiss\nhas designed it to serve as a link\nbetween laboratory and layman in\nthe food field, interpreting modern\nscientific knowledge in the language\nof the home maker, giving her the\nelemental facts regarding new dis\ncoveries and the part played by\nfood in building and maintaining\nhealth.\nEvery woman wants to know what\nfoods will benefit her family and\nwhy, and that is just the informa\ntion that Mr. Goudiss will give\nWatch for the articles each week,\nmake a scrap book of them for\nready reference. They contain valu\nab\u2019e information every home maker\nhas been wanting.\nCOMMISSIONERS MEET\nThe State Association of County Commissioners met in Minneapolis\nlast week to discuss mutual problems. Dr. Geo. W. Diepenbrock,\ncenter, above, is president of the association. With him are W. C.\nMinks of Minnesota Lake, secretary, and Frank W. Hanson, of Rush\nCity, vice president.\nMrs. Parker, Miss Wilkin\nHosts to Drama Club.\nThe March meeting of the Ely Music\nDrama club was held Monday at the\nhome of Mrs. O. W. Parker with Miss\nElizabeth Wilkin as assistant hostess.\nThe program was on \u201cThe New York\nSeason\u201d with Miss Naana Forbes in\ncharge.\nMiss Forbes read a paper on the sub\nject, written by Mrs. M. W. Peterson,\nwho is absent from the city. Following\nthis Miss Forbes read criticisms on the\ntwo leading New York plays, \u201cMice and\nMen\u201d and \u201cSusan and God.\u201d These\ncriticisms were by the noted dramatic\ncritics, Ivor Brown of the London\nTimes; Brooks Atkinson of the New\nYork Times, and B. Rosenfield of the\nDallas Morning News.\nPictures mounted on cardboard of\noutstanding New York actors and plays\nillustrated the program. Mrs. Stanley\nAdkins gave her impressions of the\nplay \u201cSusan and God\u201d which she had\nseen in New York recently.\nMiss Forbes ended the program read\ning short selections from \u201cMice and\nMen\u201d and cuttings from the play,\n\u201cSusan and God.\u201d\nThe final music meeting of the year\nwill be held at the home of Mrs. B.\nO. Strachan on March 21st.\nENGAGEMENT ANNOUNCED.\nWalter Brzezinski returned early in\nthe week from a trip through the\nsouthern states. He returned to Ely\nfrom Texas and says that he prefers\nthe business outlook nd climatic con\nditions of this state to that of the\nsouth. His engagement to Miss Ethel\nMay Cameron of Brainerd has been\nannounced. The marriage will take\nplace at the Catholic church in this\ncity on April 18. Mr. Brzezinski op\nerates the Brandt Sign Company of\nthis city.\nWASHINGTON P.-T. A.\nThe last meeting of the Washington\nP.-T. A. was held in the Memorial\nbuilding. Miss Ratzlaff, supervisor of\nthe Ely elementary grade schools dis\ncussed the subject of \u201cConstructive\nFactors for Mental Health.\u201d The talk\nTHURSDAY, MARCH 10, 1930.\nHEAR TALK ON\nAERIAL MAPS\nWm. Kendrick Discusses Old\nand New Superior Forest\nMaps at Club Meet.\n\u201cBetween 700 and 800 unnamed and\nuncharted lakes were disclosed in the\nrecent aerial survey conducted by the\nU. S. Forest Service in the Superior\nNational Forest,\u201d said W. A. Kendrick\nin his talk on \u201cMaps\u201d made before the\nSt. Andrews club at the meeting, Fri\nday evening.\nBesides telling of the new contours\ncharted for the country by the new\nsurvey, he told of the many oddities in\nthe old survey and maps disclosed by\nthe aerial survey which accurately\nshowed every portage bay, forest and\ngeological formation. He characterized\nthe new map as the most accurate and\ntruthful of any so far published. Mr.\nKendrick also told of the obstacles en\ncountered by the surveying parties in\nmaking the old maps and the chances\nfor inaccuracies while the new surveys\nwere checked and double-checked by\naccurate aerial photographs and field\nmen who went over the ground, foot by\nfoot.\nForty were present at the meeting and\nwere served a most delightful dinner by\nthe committee made up of George Ed\nwards, Byrd Brownell, Ernest Bailey,\nLauren Leino. Ernest Dargis and Robert\nCarlson. Sig Olson led the community\nsinging to the piano accompaniments\nof Miss Peggy McMahan. In the ab\nsence of President Wilson Carlson, who\nwas away at Minneapolis, William\nJones, Sr., was in charge of the meet\ning.\nwas very beneficial and instructive to\nthe parents and teachers. Miss Mary\nHutar sang two delightful selections,\naccompanied by Mrs. Charles Merhar.\nCommunity singing closed the program\nafter which refreshments were served\nat the cafeteria.","height":"29031","width":"21264"}}
